# Docsignore — what to keep OUT of spec and architecture docs
#
# Spec and architecture docs describe the protocol and its generic composition
# model. They should read as if no example application exists yet — any developer
# should be able to follow the spec and build their own app contract.
#
# This file states exclusion *principles*, each with known examples.
# Apply the principle to new cases even if they are not listed here.
#
# Referenced by CLAUDE.md Section B5.


## 1. No concrete app contract names
#
# Principle: Spec and architecture docs describe the *library* and *protocol*,
# not any particular application built on top of them. Naming a specific app
# contract couples the protocol docs to one implementation and misleads readers
# into thinking the protocol is limited to that use case.
#
# Where they belong: integration guide, tutorials, example walkthroughs.
#
# Known examples:
#   ExampleMigrationApp, ExampleApp, NftMigrationApp, ExampleNFT


## 2. No app-specific storage types or business logic
#
# Principle: The architecture should describe tiers and composition boundaries,
# not what any particular app stores or does. Saying "Application tier contracts
# import library functions and add app-specific logic" is correct. Listing the
# specific storage types or operations of one app is not.
#
# Where they belong: integration guide (storage patterns section), example code.
#
# Known examples:
#   BalanceSet, PublicMutable (when cited as app storage, not as Aztec primitives)
#   "minting tokens on claim", "decrementing supply"


## 3. No hardcoded implementation limits from example apps
#
# Principle: If a limit (e.g. batch size N=1) exists only because an example
# app hardcodes it, don't present it as a protocol property. The library
# supports the general case — document that instead.
#
# Known examples:
#   "ExampleApp currently hardcodes N = 1"
